## 2. Connecting GitHub to Semgrep

"Semgrep is a tool that automatically scans code and flags security issues before they reach production — things like risky code patterns or outdated third-party packages with known vulnerabilities.

Setting it up was a quick, guided process:
1. I signed into Semgrep.
2. From the Projects page, I clicked 'Scan new project.'
3. I selected GitHub as the source.
4. I did a one-time authorization, similar to logging into any app with your GitHub account.
5. I picked the specific repo to scan — first DVWA, our intentionally vulnerable test app, then separately my dealership app.
6. Semgrep pulled in the code and ran its full security checks automatically.

Once that connection is made, Semgrep keeps watching that code going forward — every finding I'm about to show came out of that same one-time setup."

