## 3. Finding one — SQL injection (DVWA, via GitHub)

*(Screen move: open the finding — `laravel-native-sql-injection`, ID 843313342.)*

"Point to the title: This is a finding from Semgrep on DVWA, our test app.

Point to 'Critical severity' and 'Medium confidence': These are two different things. Severity tells you how bad it would be if this were real — SQL injection is always rated seriously because it can expose an entire database. Confidence tells you how sure the tool is that this exact spot is actually exploitable. Medium confidence means it's not fully certain, which is exactly why it's flagged the way it is below.

Point to the green 'Likely false positive' box: This is the tool's own AI double-checking itself. Before this piece of user input ever reaches the database, the code forces it to become a plain number — so there's nothing left for an attacker to manipulate. It does add a note that the logic around this code should still be reviewed separately, just to be safe.

Point to the Finding description text: Even though it called this a likely false positive, it still wrote out exactly how an attack could happen in theory, step by step. That's useful for a developer because it shows the risk pattern clearly, even on code that happens to be safe right now — so they don't repeat that pattern elsewhere.

Point to the code panel, Line 19 'Source' and Line 23 'Sink': This shows the journey of the data — Line 19 is where the user's input first enters the program, Line 23 is where it finally gets used in the database command. The tool traces that whole path automatically."

**Remediation (technical)**: "Replace the string-interpolated query with a prepared statement using bound parameters — in PHP, that's PDO with `bindParam()`, or alternatively adopt an ORM layer so user input is always passed as a bound value rather than concatenated into the SQL string. That removes the injection vector regardless of whether the input happens to be pre-validated upstream."

