## 4. Finding two — supply chain (my dealership app, via GitHub)

*(Screen move: open the `serialize-javascript` supply chain finding.)*

"Point to the title: This finding isn't about code I wrote — it's about an outside package my app relies on. We don't write every part of an app ourselves; we use existing building blocks made by other developers, and this one has a known flaw.

Point to 'Medium severity': Not critical — it could slow things down under certain conditions, but it's not a doorway into stealing data.

Point to 'Reachability unknown': The tool is being honest about a limit here — it hasn't confirmed whether my app actually uses the risky part of this package. It's flagging it because it could be a problem, not because it's proven to be one.

Point to 'EPSS: 0.5% (Low)': This is a public, real-world score estimating how likely this exact flaw is to actually be exploited in the wild — under 1% is very low."

**Remediation (technical)**: "Upgrade `serialize-javascript` from version 6.0.2 to 7.0.5, the patched release Semgrep identifies directly in the finding — a dependency version bump in `package-lock.json`, no code changes required."

